<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="178" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="23.[144,1104,309,405]" box="[144,265,309,333]" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">
<heading box="[144,265,309,333]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="23" pageNumber="178" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[144,265,309,333]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[144,1104,309,405]" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">
The specific name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cazorla and Spinelli" authorityYear="2014" box="[351,514,349,373]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Stilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monomorphica">
<emphasis box="[351,514,349,373]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">monomorphica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to the lack of secondary sexual dimorphism in males of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="178" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[144,1103,491,681]" box="[144,260,491,514]" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">
<heading box="[144,260,491,514]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="23" pageNumber="178" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[144,260,491,514]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">Discussion</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[144,1103,491,681]" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">
This is the only species of 
<taxonomicName box="[446,567,530,554]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Stilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[446,567,530,554]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">Stilobezzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[761,911,530,554]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Stilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Acanthohelea">
<emphasis box="[761,911,530,554]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">Acanthohelea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
without obvious male secondary sexual characters. The male genitalia of this new species greatly resembles those of 
<emphasis box="[370,386,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">S</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ingram &amp; Macfie" authorityYear="1931" box="[405,515,593,617]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Stilobezzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varia" subGenus="Acanthohelea">
(
<emphasis box="[413,432,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">A</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[460,515,594,617]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="178">varia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but males of that species differ by their broader sternite 9, with a broad, shallow posteromedian excavation, a pale and slender gonostylus and a gonocoxite with a short, mesal tubercle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
